Quiggy’s  (Tat)<br />
Coruscant:  Jedi Council Chamber<br />
   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Strategy:  quick note...I forgot to mention something that was in my article that I want to put here.  Always play Wise Advice shield...you can&#39;t afford to lose Route (v).<br />
<br /><br />
[edit- Yoda IS in the deck.  end edit]<br />
<br />
Well, here’s my take on post v6 WHAP (thanx again to Brian Fred!)  Anyway, I designed this for MY meta, hence the lack of much walker hate.  If you want to know more about killing walkers, read my article I HAP for WHAP, cards like Heroic Sacrifice (v), more Atrocities, T-47 Battle Formation etc can all help out.  Anywho…here goes.<br />
<br />
Turn one:  Activate on their first turn, and when you activate 3 pull Secure Route (v).  There is a pretty good chance you can flip first turn with all the activation plus 3 amidalas plus one Sabe plus 3 control/TVs.  If you’re going against a fast damage deck, you definitely want to flip ASAP, if not, you might want to hold off until you have evasion and stuff.  <br />
<br />
After that:  There really is no formula for this deck.  It’s more reactive.  Obviously you want to get your damage going.  Send mains out to knock off his guys, but keep the Throne Room safe.  Make use of Flash (v) and Disorder (v) and Route (v) to keep getting cards out of your lost pile.  You love battling with this deck, but on your terms.  It’s A Trap! is fun as well as Houjix.  Set up infinite loops with Route (v)!  They can’t grab everything…(sinister laughter)<br />
<br />
Card Choices:<br />
<br />
I go into more detail about this in my article, but I figure I’ll quickly rundown some card explanations here.<br />
<br />
Horace Vancil and Leesub Sirln- Horace forces them to reveal a card at random to you.  They put it in Used or lose a force.  If they keep it, you can use Leesub to reveal the same card (not random) and guess what kind of card it is.  It’s then lost anyway.  Damage gets nasty with this deck even if Decree (v) is out.  One from obj+one from Mace+two drains of two+plus one from Artillery+one from Leesub maybe) that’s an average guess of 8 damage per turn!  And there’s definitely the potential to do more.  That’s so huge when combined with all the crazy tricks you have for getting stuff back.  <br />
<br />
Why Padme?  This is a personal choice, I like her pulling out the Jedi, plus she’s safe from weapons.  Definitely could be another queenie, up to you.  <br />
<br />
I Hope She’s All Right-Yeah, with no space, I think this card’s essential.  It will be a damage race and this will help give you an edge.  Just keep knocking him off of battleground sites, while constantly getting characters and stuff back with all your crazy tech.  Note:  There’s NO character Disorder (v) can’t get back with this deck.  That’s one reason why I chose to go with no EPP Quiggy.<br />
<br />
Matching weapons?- My choice again because of the damage issue.  This helps to compensate for Decree (v).  Your drains will be bigger with these sabers, plus you can use Artillery with the blasters.  Also, Amidala’s blaster is definitely underused.  It’s like a Lateral Damage for characters…it lasts beyond the battle until the character leaves the table!<br />
<br />
Don’t Do That Again-  I hate first turn Executor (cough cough CCT).  You’d be surprised how many decks can be totally screwed up or at least drastically slowed down if their Mob Pts is suspended before they can use it.  This should often slow down their set up in space, giving you more time to get damage rolling.  Which again, is kinda the whole point of the deck.  You need all the help you can get against space decks.  I play the shield too in case I need it if the effect isn’t out.<br />
<br />
K’lor’slug (v) – Necessary in this deck.  If someone like Jerus J dies in the middle of a battle, you’re sunk.  This keeps your mains alive ‘til the end of a battle, which is a big help.  Also helps a wee bit with Bad Feeling Have I if you see it.<br />
<br />
On to matchups:  (Walkers and CCT are cut and pasted from I HAP for WHAP)<br />
<br />
Walkers:  While building a WHAP deck, I constantly thought of how it could counter walkers, I knew it wasn’t going to be easy.  Walkers are so popular right now tho that it would be foolish to build a deck without considering it at all.  Here’s my thinking:<br />
<br />
First action- get out the DDTA shield.  Pull Heroic Sacrifice v (I’d definitely put it in if I were playing at a big tourney).  I know that most walker decks love to abuse Blizzard 4 to pull Vader to blow the poor defenseless shield generators.  This will punish them, at least a little bit.  Plus, it reduces Blizzard 4’s power and gets rid of its ability to draw battle destiny.  It’s possible to attack now, but still I would never ever ever recommend it unless you’re ready for Ice Storm, Trample, or whatever.  Pack a Houjix before ever visiting Hoth.  OK, again damage minimization is the name of the game.  Flash (v) is a great friend in this matchup.  Atrocity (v) the damage from blowing the generators, and atrocity the direct damage after that, as well as whatever drains you can.  You can use T-47 Battle Formation to get rid of Garrison, but Sense works as well.  Don’t rely on the sense necessarily, as Controls are all too common.  Hopefully Leesub or Horace will help you get a key card out of their hand, this will be a tough matchup.<br />
<br />
Here’s another idea I had.  This would certainly be a lot of fun, and I think it just might work.  Pack a whole bunch of Imperial Atrocities, I’ll say six for now.  Make 4 of them v and 2 regular.  Use the v ones as much as possible to reduce as much damage as you can as fast as you can.  Oh, and above all DO NOT FLIP.  You heard me, keep Amidala out of the throne room.  If you flip you ruin the whole strategy.  Then, once you have the 4 virtual atrocities out, wait for Garrison.  When Garrison comes, BAM!  Play the non-v Atrocity and they lose 10.  If they do it again they lose 12.  I’m not sure if this would really work or not, but it sure would be fun.  Worst-case scenario you’d have a bunch of sixes in your deck.  If this works for anyone, let me know, I’ll try it if walkers get to be huge around my area.<br />
<br />
CCT:  Another reason I wanted to make WHAP was because I was sick of losing my Han.  It’s really annoying to have to battle out on Cloud City to free the popsicle.  With WHAP, I have no problem with Han chilling in the Security Tower.  They can keep Lando too.  You can Atrocity (v) their drain at the tower, and you should have little trouble getting set up on Naboo.  Feel free to harass them on CC, but don’t get too crazy.  As always there just isn’t anything you can do about their space, but you can stop Occupation by knocking them off of battlegrounds.  Keep the damage up and you should do well.  They should be hard-pressed do really get Decree (v) rolling unless they play a lot of space.  This is definitely winnable.<br />
<br />
Hunt Down:  They’ll probably put a first turn Vader or Palpy at the throne room.  It happens to the best of us.  You might want to keep visage on the table, because of all of your Jedi but it’s up to you.  Battle the dark Jedi, then OOC them.  Remember to abuse your interrupts!  This will be a fun and interactive game, and visage should be hurting him as much as you.  Big difference- you have Flash (v), Route (v), and Disorder (v).  Be ready for battles often, evasion will frustrate him.<br />
<br />
SYC Fear/Other Big Blue:  Damage early, damage often.  Try to make I Hope She’s All Right work.  Just knock them off of sites whenever you can.  No need to worry about Put All Sections on Alert!  Abuse your retrieving effects and junk, and damage minimizers.  Alter Fear if you can.  If they don’t grab it…get it back and Alter it again!  Definitely a tough matchup, but your damage should be enough to give you the win if you play smart.<br />
<br />
Combat:  Disorder (v) is your friend.  Make sure to use the anti-combat shield too.  It’s fun to put a Jedi on the opposite end of Naboo from Maul.  Put a scrub in front of Maul.  Thanks to the shield, he can’t battle you.  And if he moves away, you get a free drain site!  You are definitely advantaged here.  OOC Maul and you will win every time.  Ref. III Quiggy is fun for combat.<br />
<br />
Court/Scum:  They can damage you.  You can damage them more.  This shouldn’t be tricky, just knock them off of sites as opportunities present themselves.  These decks aren’t super popular right now, and there’s a good reason for that.<br />
<br />
Deal:  Yuck.  This might be tricky.  No Menace Fades for you, but their drains will all be capped at two, which is nice.  If this is heavy in your area, you might want to pack a Free Ride combo.  You’ll probably have to go to cloud city and try to clear some sites.  Not an easy matchup, they’re going to have a ton of characters.  If you can stay flipped tho, and can make use of all your crazy retrieval while battling, it will be winnable.<br />
<br />
Watto:  Speed Watto is no fun.  If you can get to Watto and OOC him, more power to you.  He’s probably packing a ton of cheese to stop battles, but you have SAC and enough force for Projective Telepathy.  Your damage should be greater than his, and remember you can get a lot of your stuff back.  Should be interactive and fun.<br />
<br />
I think that’s it for the main matchups, if I forgot anything let me know and I’ll edit it in.  Again, this is designed for my meta as it stands right now.  I’d definitely make some changes if I was to take it to a DPC or something.  Remember, your strength is crazy damage while minimizing your opponent’s.  If I missed anything big it’s probably in my article I HAP for WHAP.  No matter what you’ll have a blast playing this deck, and I see it being very successful.<br />
<br />
Constructive criticism welcome.<br />
<br />
Aglets<br />
<br />
